WEBVTT

00:05.918 --> 00:07.050
PREVIOUSLY ON
"PUSHING DAISIES"...

00:07.094 --> 00:08.312
YOU ONLY GOT A MINUTE.
I KNOW.

00:08.356 --> 00:09.922
60 SECONDS.
I KNOW.

00:09.966 --> 00:11.011
[ INHALES SHARPLY ]

00:11.054 --> 00:12.838
OHH!

00:12.882 --> 00:15.450
WHAT IF YOU
DIDN'T HAVE TO BE DEAD?

00:15.493 --> 00:17.843
YOU TOUCH MURDER VICTIMS,
YOU ASK WHO KILLED THEM.

00:17.887 --> 00:20.237
YOU TOUCH THEM AGAIN,
THEY GO BACK TO BEING DEAD,

00:20.281 --> 00:22.239
AND YOU COLLECT
THE REWARD?NOBODY CAN KNOW.

00:22.283 --> 00:24.241
I CAN'T EVEN HUG YOU?YOU CAN'T TOUCH ME.

00:24.285 --> 00:26.026
SO A KISS IS
OUT OF THE QUESTION?

00:26.069 --> 00:29.464
WHO'S THE FUNNY GIRL
STUCK TO NED?CHILDHOOD SWEETHEART.

00:29.507 --> 00:31.683
HE DIGS HER IN A WAY
HE DEFINITELY DOESN'T DIG YOU.

00:31.727 --> 00:33.468
Chuck: THANK YOU FOR
BRINGING ME BACK TO LIFE.

00:33.511 --> 00:35.078
PEOPLE AREN'T USED
TO THIS SORT OF THING.

00:35.122 --> 00:36.645
ISSUES OF MORALITY,
HOW COME SHE'S NOT DEAD ANYMORE?

00:36.688 --> 00:38.690
YOU UNDERSTAND
YOU CAN'T SEE YOUR AUNTS.

00:38.734 --> 00:39.691
IT'D BE A DISASTER.

00:39.735 --> 00:40.910
[ DOORBELL RINGS ]

00:40.953 --> 00:43.130
THIS PIE
SMELLS DELICIOUS.

00:43.173 --> 00:45.306
WE RECENTLY LOST
OUR NIECE.

00:45.349 --> 00:47.699
YOUR NIECE,
CHARLOTTE CHARLES, IS DEAD?

00:47.743 --> 00:49.179
PRESENTLY?

00:58.188 --> 01:01.365
Narrator: AT THIS VERY MOMENT,
IN THE TOWN OF NORTH THRUSH,

01:01.409 --> 01:04.673
YOUNG NED WAS...

01:04.716 --> 01:07.067
LONELY.

01:07.110 --> 01:10.374
UNABLE TO MAKE FRIENDS AT
THE LONGBURROW SCHOOL FOR BOYS,

01:10.418 --> 01:13.334
HE OFTEN FOUND HIMSELF
PLAYING ALONE,

01:13.377 --> 01:16.206
WITH NOTHING BUT MEMORIES
OF HAPPIER TIMES

01:16.250 --> 01:18.643
TO KEEP HIS COMPANY.

01:18.687 --> 01:21.907
WHAT YOUNG NED DID NOT REALIZE
WAS THAT,

01:21.951 --> 01:25.824
BEYOND THE MEADOW
AND UNDER THE SAME ORANGE SKY,

01:25.868 --> 01:28.740
SOMEONE HE LOVED
WAS REMEMBERING HIM.

01:30.438 --> 01:32.918
HIS DOG, DIGBY.

01:32.962 --> 01:37.575
IN FACT, THREE DAYS PRIOR,
DIGBY HAD MADE A DECISION.

01:37.619 --> 01:40.796
WEARIED BY HIS OWN LONELINESS
BACK IN COEUR d'COEURS

01:40.839 --> 01:45.148
AND SENSING HIS MASTER'S SORROW,
DIGBY SET OUT ON A MISSION.

01:48.978 --> 01:51.807
UNCERTAIN AS TO
HIS EXACT DESTINATION,

01:51.850 --> 01:54.418
HE VENTURED
INTO THE GREAT UNKNOWN,

01:54.462 --> 01:56.942
GUIDED ONLY BY THE COMPASS
OF HIS HEART.

01:56.986 --> 01:58.683
[ WHINES ]

02:03.819 --> 02:05.429
[ ALARM RINGING ]

02:05.473 --> 02:07.475
Narrator:
DESPITE NUMEROUS DISTRACTIONS,

02:07.518 --> 02:11.000
[ SIREN WAILING ]DIGBY WAS DETERMINED
TO FIND YOUNG NED,

02:11.043 --> 02:13.916
THE BOY WHO HAD GIVEN HIM
A SECOND CHANCE AT LIFE...

02:13.959 --> 02:18.138
AND WHO WAS HIS BEST FRIEND.

02:23.273 --> 02:28.887
UPON DOING SO, DIGBY PROVED THAT
LOVE CAN OVERCOME ANY OBSTACLE.

02:30.933 --> 02:33.631
THE REUNION
WAS BITTERSWEET, HOWEVER,

02:33.675 --> 02:35.764
AS THEY INSTANTLY REMEMBERED
THE RESTRICTIONS

02:35.807 --> 02:37.766
OF THEIR FRIENDSHIP.

02:37.809 --> 02:43.424
THEY COULD NOT TOUCH,
OR DIGBY WOULD DIE.

02:45.948 --> 02:48.298
STILL, IT WAS ENOUGH.

02:48.342 --> 02:49.604
[ PANTING ]

02:56.785 --> 03:01.181
Narrator:
THAT DAY, DIGBY VOWED HE WOULD
NEVER AGAIN ALLOW HIMSELF

03:01.224 --> 03:03.313
TO BE SEPARATED FROM HIS MASTER.

03:06.882 --> 03:11.756
THE PIE MAKER DID NOT WISH
TO BE SEPARATED FROM CHUCK,

03:11.800 --> 03:15.847
WHO, IN TURN, DID NOT WISH
TO BE SEPARATED FROM HER AUNTS,

03:15.891 --> 03:17.414
LILY AND VIVIAN,

03:17.458 --> 03:20.983
WHO CONTINUED TO BE CHALLENGED
BY SOCIAL PHOBIAS.

03:21.026 --> 03:23.115
UNBEKNOWNST TO THE PIE MAKER,

03:23.159 --> 03:26.423
CHUCK SECRETLY BAKED
HOMEOPATHIC MOOD ENHANCERS

03:26.467 --> 03:28.425
INTO PIES FOR HER AUNTS,

03:28.469 --> 03:29.992
HOPING THAT A SLICE A DAY

03:30.035 --> 03:32.168
WOULD HERBALLY LIFT
THEIR SPIRITS.

03:32.212 --> 03:34.214
OH, YOU'RE UP EARLY.

03:34.257 --> 03:36.607
UM -- OH,
I COULDN'T SLEEP.

03:36.651 --> 03:38.348
LUMPY MATTRESS?
LUMPY DREAMS.

03:38.392 --> 03:40.307
WHICH ARE A LOT MORE
VIVID NOW THAN THEY
WERE BEFORE I DIED.

03:40.350 --> 03:41.525
ISN'T THAT INTERESTING?

03:41.569 --> 03:43.397
JUST ONE OF THOSE...
LITTLE THINGS.

03:43.440 --> 03:44.833
WHAT ARE THOSE?

03:44.876 --> 03:48.053
OH, I, UH...

03:48.097 --> 03:49.533
GOT BIT.

03:49.577 --> 03:50.882
THOSE ARE BEESTINGS.

03:50.926 --> 03:52.797
HOW'D YOU GET STUNG
BY SO MANY BEES?

03:52.841 --> 03:55.104
AND WHAT HAPPENED TO THE BEES
THAT STUNG YOU?

03:55.147 --> 03:56.323
THAT'S A SUICIDE ATTACK.

03:56.366 --> 03:57.628
NOT IN THIS CASE.

03:57.672 --> 03:59.151
THEY, UH, SORT OF
STUNG ME, DIED,

03:59.195 --> 04:01.632
THEN THEY FLEW AWAY AGAIN,
AND SOME OTHER BEES DIED.

04:01.676 --> 04:04.069
[ CHUCKLES ]

04:04.113 --> 04:07.072
DO YOU THINK THEIR HONEY
TASTES DIFFERENT

04:07.116 --> 04:08.509
'CAUSE THEY DIED?

04:08.552 --> 04:10.032
WOULDN'T THAT BE
INTERESTING?

04:10.075 --> 04:11.599
JUST ONE OF
THOSE LITTLE THINGS.

04:11.642 --> 04:14.341
I WANT TO SHOW YOU
SOMETHING.

04:15.907 --> 04:18.083
Chuck: WHAT IS IT?

04:25.003 --> 04:26.222
BEES!

04:26.266 --> 04:27.397
YOURBEES.

04:27.441 --> 04:28.964
MYBEES?
YOU MEAN...

04:29.007 --> 04:30.748
NO, NOT THOSE BEES --
NEW BEES.

04:30.792 --> 04:32.315
TECHNICALLY,
STILL YOUR BEES,

04:32.359 --> 04:35.405
JUST...NOT THE BEES
THAT YOU KNEW.

04:35.449 --> 04:38.408
BUT I'M SURE
THEY'RE EQUALLY NICE.

04:38.452 --> 04:40.976
YOU DO REALIZE THAT BEEKEEPING
WITHIN CITY LIMITS

04:41.019 --> 04:42.499
IS COMPLETELY ILLEGAL.
YES.

04:42.543 --> 04:44.936
AND I'M ALMOST SURE
I DON'T CARE.

04:44.980 --> 04:48.592
WELL, I CAN NOT CARE ENOUGH
FOR THE BOTH OF US.

04:48.636 --> 04:49.985
[ EXHALES DEEPLY ]

04:50.028 --> 04:52.117
WE CAN PLANT WILD FLOWERS
ON ROOFTOPS

04:52.161 --> 04:55.425
AND BE UNORTHODOX
URBAN HONEY PIONEERS.

04:55.469 --> 04:57.514
[ CHUCKLES ]
THANK YOU.

04:57.558 --> 04:59.299
THANK YOU.
THANK YOU.

04:59.342 --> 05:01.605
IF I COULD HUG YOU RIGHT NOW --
I KNOW THAT I CAN'T, BUT --

05:01.649 --> 05:03.955
[ SIGHS ]
JUST KNOW THAT I WANT TO.

05:05.130 --> 05:06.480
I DO.

05:09.831 --> 05:12.355
Narrator:
AS CHUCK CONSIDERED HER FUTURE

05:12.399 --> 05:16.794
AS AN UNORTHODOX
URBAN HONEY PIONEER...

05:16.838 --> 05:20.624
OLIVE SNOOK CONSIDERED
HOW THE MAN SHE LOVED

05:20.668 --> 05:22.887
SEEMED TO BE IN LOVE
WITH SOMEONE ELSE.

05:22.931 --> 05:24.454
[ WHINES ]

05:27.631 --> 05:31.331
Narrator: HER AFFECTION FOR
THE PIE MAKER HAD NOT WAVERED,

05:31.374 --> 05:35.944
DESPITE THE ROMANTIC THREAT
OF A DEAD GIRL WHO WASN'TDEAD.

05:35.987 --> 05:38.816
I DIDN'T KNOW
YOU COULD DO THAT.

05:38.860 --> 05:40.340
Narrator:
ON THE CONTRARY,

05:40.383 --> 05:42.385
OLIVE'S RESOLVE
HAD ONLY INCREASED

05:42.429 --> 05:44.822
SINCE THE REALIZATION
THAT CHUCK, INDEED,

05:44.866 --> 05:46.171
WAS SUPPOSED TO BE DEAD.

05:46.215 --> 05:47.651
GOOD MORNING!

05:47.695 --> 05:50.393
OLIVE ASSUMED CHUCK HAD FAKED
HER OWN DEATH.

05:50.437 --> 05:52.656
SHE WOULD KEEP THE SECRET
FOR NOW,

05:52.700 --> 05:55.355
AS CHUCK KEPT HERSECRET
FROM THE PIE MAKER.

05:55.398 --> 05:56.617
THERE'S A PIE IN MY OVEN.

05:56.660 --> 05:59.141
OH, UH, THAT'S MINE.
I WAS PRACTICING.

05:59.184 --> 06:01.926
IT SMELLS LIKE CHEESE.
IS IT QUICHE?

06:01.970 --> 06:03.319
I BAKED MONASTERY GOUDA
INTO THE CRUST --

06:03.363 --> 06:04.929
TART APPLE FILLING.

06:04.973 --> 06:06.757
I THOUGHT I'D TRY IT.

06:06.801 --> 06:09.499
Olive: YOU KNOW
WHAT WOULD BE DELICIOUS?

06:09.543 --> 06:12.546
PEAR WITH GRUYèRE CRUST.
BET THAT'D BE REAL GOOD.

06:12.589 --> 06:14.852
YEAH, IT WOULD.

06:14.896 --> 06:16.593
Narrator:
UNBEKNOWNST TO CHUCK,

06:16.637 --> 06:18.813
OLIVE UNDERSTOOD
THE DELICIOUSNESS

06:18.856 --> 06:20.336
OF PEAR AND GRUYèRE...

06:20.380 --> 06:21.772
THANK YOU.

06:21.816 --> 06:23.426
Narrator: ...BECAUSE
SHE SECRETLY DELIVERED

06:23.470 --> 06:27.212
THAT FIRST MOOD-ENHANCING PIE
TO AUNTS LILY AND VIVIAN,

06:27.256 --> 06:28.866
AS SHE WOULD DELIVER
THIS ONE...

06:28.910 --> 06:30.520
[ THUD, SQUAWK ]

06:30.564 --> 06:33.523
Narrator: ...BUT NOT BEFORE
A COLLISION OCCURRED.

06:33.567 --> 06:36.874
OH!
I THINK SHE'S DEAD!

06:36.918 --> 06:38.441
CAN YOU FEEL A HEARTBEAT?

06:38.485 --> 06:41.531
I DON'T...
D-DO HEARTBEATS.

06:41.575 --> 06:44.839
WELL, THEY FEEL LIKE THIS.
COME HERE.

06:44.882 --> 06:47.450
THUMP, THUMP.

06:47.494 --> 06:49.060
THUMP, THUMP.

06:49.104 --> 06:52.020
THUMP, THUMP.
THUMP, THUMP.

06:52.063 --> 06:53.021
[ HEART BEATING ]

06:53.064 --> 06:54.283
IS THAT A DEAD BIRD?

06:54.326 --> 06:55.240
WHY ARE YOU TOUCHING
A DEAD BIRD?

06:55.284 --> 06:56.807
THROW THAT AWAY.

06:56.851 --> 06:58.243
IT'S SWIMMING WITH DISEASE,
AND YOU SERVE FOOD.

06:58.287 --> 06:59.506
DON'T BE SUCH
A DRAMA QUEEN.

06:59.549 --> 07:01.159
BESIDES,
IT DOESN'T LOOK DISEASED.

07:01.203 --> 07:04.424
IT'S DEAD, AND IT'S A BIRD.
IT'S DISEASED.

07:04.467 --> 07:06.121
[ CHIRPING ]

07:06.164 --> 07:08.906
[ GASPS ]
IT'S A MIRACLE BIRD!

07:08.950 --> 07:11.474
IT'S SWIMMING IN MIRACLES,
NOTDISEASE!

07:11.518 --> 07:12.736
MAYBE ISHOULD HOLD IT.

07:12.780 --> 07:14.259
OH, NO, REALLY,
DO YOU HAVE TO?

07:14.303 --> 07:15.565
SHE'S OBVIOUSLY
BEEN THROUGH A LOT,

07:15.609 --> 07:17.437
AND SHE SEEMS REALLY HAPPY
TO BE HERE.

07:18.481 --> 07:21.441
Narrator: HAVING BROUGHT
A DEAD THING BACK TO LIFE,

07:21.484 --> 07:24.922
THE PIE MAKER FRETTED OVER WHO,
OR WHAT, WOULD PAY

07:24.966 --> 07:27.447
FOR THATLIFE WITH ITS OWN.

07:28.926 --> 07:30.014
I WONDER HOW
SHE LOST HER WING.

07:30.058 --> 07:32.103
DOESN'T SEEM TO BE
IN ANY PAIN.

07:32.147 --> 07:33.453
SHE'S PROBABLY NOT IN PAIN.

07:33.496 --> 07:34.497
BUT WHAT DO I KNOW?
I'M NOT A BIRD.

07:34.541 --> 07:35.672
PIGEON.
PIGEON.

07:35.716 --> 07:36.934
UH, PIGEON-TOED
AS A CHILD,

07:36.978 --> 07:38.283
BUT ORTHOPEDIC SHOES
SOLVED THAT.

07:38.327 --> 07:40.024
[ Chuckling ] YEAH.

07:40.068 --> 07:42.592
WHAT IS THE RATE OF EXCHANGE
ON THE LIFE OF A BIRD?

07:42.636 --> 07:44.594
'CAUSE IF IT'S EQUAL TO
OR GREATER THAN MINE,

07:44.638 --> 07:46.596
I NEED TO GET BACK
TO MY CAR.

07:46.640 --> 07:48.511
I'M MORE CONCERNED
FOR THAT SQUIRREL.

07:49.730 --> 07:51.296
OH.

07:51.340 --> 07:54.038
DON'T YOU WORRY. I KNOW
JUST WHAT TO DO WITH YOU.

07:54.082 --> 07:56.867
I RECENTLY MADE THE ACQUAINTANCE
OF A PAIR OF BIRD LOVERS.

07:56.911 --> 07:58.521
I'LL CONSULT THEM.

07:58.565 --> 08:01.132
Narrator: OLIVE WAS REFERRING
TO AUNTS LILY AND VIVIAN.

08:01.176 --> 08:03.526
REALLY? IUSED TO KNOW
A PAIR OF BIRD LOVERS.

08:03.570 --> 08:06.964
Narrator: CHUCK ALSOREFERRED
TO AUNTS LILY AND VIVIAN.

08:07.008 --> 08:09.880
USEDTO?
DID THEY DIE?

08:09.924 --> 08:11.621
A DEATH WAS INVOLVED.

08:11.665 --> 08:13.231
HOW UNFORTUNATE.

08:13.275 --> 08:16.626
Narrator: THEY WERE BOTH SO BUSY
REFERRING AND INFERRING,

08:16.670 --> 08:19.281
THEY FAILED TO NOTICE
THAT 60 SECONDS HAD PASSED.

08:19.324 --> 08:23.198
THE PIE MAKER COULD NOT AFFORD
SUCH A LUXURY.

08:24.329 --> 08:25.896
[ THUD ]

08:26.506 --> 08:28.638
IT'S RAINING DEAD BIRDS!

08:28.682 --> 08:31.162
[ AIRPLANE ENGINE BUZZING ]

08:31.206 --> 08:34.035
WHAT'S GOING ON UP THERE?

08:35.776 --> 08:38.518
Narrator: WHAT WAS GOING ON
UP THERE WAS THIS --

08:38.561 --> 08:41.825
AN OUT-OF-CONTROL CROP DUSTER
CRASHED HEADFIRST

08:41.869 --> 08:44.872
INTO THE BROADVIEW
LUXURY APARTMENT COMPLEX,

08:44.915 --> 08:47.048
KILLING THE PILOT INSTANTLY.

08:47.091 --> 08:50.268
HIS BODY WAS CATAPULTED
OUT OF THE COCKPIT

08:50.312 --> 08:53.968
AND INTO THE LIVING ROOM
OF ONE CONRAD FITCH.

08:54.011 --> 08:55.665
DOES THIS -- OH --

08:55.709 --> 08:58.189
DOES THIS QUALIFY
AS AMBULANCE-CHASING?

08:58.233 --> 09:00.061
I'M ASKING WITHOUT
ANY JUDGMENT AT ALL.

09:00.104 --> 09:01.671
IF YOU'RE ASKING
WITHOUT ANY JUDGMENT,

09:01.715 --> 09:03.020
THEN, YES, IT DOES.

09:03.064 --> 09:04.239
LOOK FOR BODY BAGS.

09:04.282 --> 09:05.675
THAT'S NOT OUR THING.

09:05.719 --> 09:07.285
YOUR THING IS WAKING UP
DEAD PEOPLE.

09:07.329 --> 09:09.287
MY THING IS FINDING DEAD PEOPLE
FOR YOU TO WAKE UP.

09:09.331 --> 09:11.986
OOH, FOUND ONE.

09:12.029 --> 09:14.554
WHY CAN'T WE JUST BE HERE AS
CONCERNED CITIZENS OF THE WORLD?

09:14.597 --> 09:16.381
BECAUSE BIG DADDY
NEEDS SOME NEW YARN.

09:16.425 --> 09:17.992
JUST BECAUSE
THERE'S A DEAD BODY

09:18.035 --> 09:19.689
DOESN'T MEAN
YOU'RE GONNA GET PAID.

09:19.733 --> 09:21.430
JUST BECAUSE THERE'S VODKA
IN MY FREEZER

09:21.473 --> 09:22.910
DOESN'T MEAN
I HAVE TO DRINK IT.

09:22.953 --> 09:24.085
WAIT, YES, IT DOES.

09:24.128 --> 09:25.695
HE'S NOT WRONG.

09:25.739 --> 09:27.175
PLANE CRASHES
INTO A BUILDING --

09:27.218 --> 09:28.698
COULD MEAN A CIVIL SUIT,
CRIMINAL SUIT, NEGLIGENCE,

09:28.742 --> 09:30.134
PAIN AND SUFFERING,
NEGLIGENT PAIN AND SUFFERING.

09:30.178 --> 09:32.441
Narrator: CHUCK FOSTERED
HER LOVE OF THE LAW

09:32.484 --> 09:35.139
BY VOLUNTEERING
AS A STAY-AT-HOME JUROR

09:35.183 --> 09:36.706
FOR A PARAPLEGIC JUDGE.

09:36.750 --> 09:39.448
WE THE JURY FIND
THE DEFENDANT GUILTY.

09:40.841 --> 09:43.060
OH, I'M SORRY.
OOH! [ GASPS ]

09:43.104 --> 09:47.064
Narrator: UNABLE TO CATCH CHUCK
WHEN SHE FELL,

09:47.108 --> 09:50.024
THE PIE MAKER WAS FORCED
TO STEP ASIDE,

09:50.067 --> 09:53.984
ALLOWING ANOTHER MAN
TO CATCH HER.

09:54.028 --> 09:56.944
[ EXHALES ]
THANK YOU.

09:56.987 --> 09:58.641
FORGIVE THE MESS.

09:58.685 --> 10:00.034
THE MAID COMES TOMORROW.

10:00.077 --> 10:02.210
GUESS I SHOULD
CANCEL THAT.

10:02.253 --> 10:03.211
DO YOU LIVE HERE?

10:03.254 --> 10:04.429
UNTIL VERY RECENTLY.

10:04.473 --> 10:06.083
CAN YOU PUT HER DOWN,
PLEASE?

10:06.127 --> 10:08.129
UNH.

10:08.172 --> 10:12.437
AT LEAST YOUR COLLECTION
OF NAUTICAL PLATES SURVIVED.

10:12.481 --> 10:14.222
[ SHATTERING ]

10:14.265 --> 10:16.441
THOSE WERE FRANKLIN MINT.

10:16.485 --> 10:18.400
OH. I'M SORRY.

10:18.443 --> 10:19.967
NO, IT'S OKAY.
I'LL BE OKAY.

10:20.010 --> 10:22.926
I WAS FEELING LIKE I NEEDED
TO SIMPLIFY MY LIFE, ANYWAY.

10:22.970 --> 10:25.842
Narrator: CHUCK'S HEART WENT OUT
TO THE MAN WITH THE PLANE

10:25.886 --> 10:27.539
IN HIS LIVING ROOM,

10:27.583 --> 10:30.281
DESPITE THE PIE MAKER WANTING
HER HEART FOR HIMSELF.

10:30.325 --> 10:34.416
SUDDENLY, AMBULANCE-CHASING
DIDN'T SEEM LIKE A BAD IDEA.

10:34.459 --> 10:36.679
[ CLEARS THROAT ]
THE AMBULANCE IS LEAVING.

10:36.723 --> 10:38.115
OH, YOU GO AHEAD.
I'M GONNA STAY HERE,

10:38.159 --> 10:39.421
SEE IF THERE'S ANYTHING
I CAN DO.

10:39.464 --> 10:40.944
I'M SURE HE'S FINE.

10:40.988 --> 10:42.119
STATISTICALLY SPEAKING,
HIS DAY CAN ONLY IMPROVE.

10:42.163 --> 10:43.338
DEAD PILOT, ON THE OTHER HAND,

10:43.381 --> 10:44.905
PROBABLY HAS LOTS
OF LAST WISHES.

10:44.948 --> 10:46.646
YEAH, LIKE MAYBE HE WISHED
HE'D HAVE TURNED LEFT.

10:46.689 --> 10:48.299
YOU DON'T NEED ME
FOR THAT.

10:48.343 --> 10:49.997
SHE'S GOT A POINT.
BUT --

10:50.040 --> 10:54.218
DON'T ARGUE WITH THE WOMAN.
WE GOT A DEAD GUY TO TALK TO.

10:54.262 --> 10:57.047
Narrator:
THE FACTS WERE THESE --

10:57.091 --> 11:00.485
ONE BRADAN CADEN,
AN AGRICULTURAL AVIATOR,

11:00.529 --> 11:05.229
WAS 53 YEARS, 21 WEEKS, 5 DAYS,
6 HOURS, AND 19 MINUTES OLD,

11:05.273 --> 11:06.883
WHEN HIS CROP DUSTER COLLIDED

11:06.927 --> 11:09.886
WITH THE BROADVIEW
LUXURY APARTMENT COMPLEX.

11:09.930 --> 11:13.411
IT WAS 17 MINUTES
AFTER THE COLLISION,

11:13.455 --> 11:17.415
AND MR. CADEN'S INSURANCE AGENT
HAD ALREADY REJECTED THE CLAIM

11:17.459 --> 11:21.898
ON HIS LIFE POLICY
BEFORETHE CLAIM WAS EVEN MADE.

11:21.942 --> 11:23.726
DID YOU SEE THE WAY
HE JUST SWEPT IN THERE?

11:23.770 --> 11:25.032
YEAH, SO?
I DON'T SWEEP.

11:25.075 --> 11:26.686
I'M NOT A SWEEPER.

11:26.729 --> 11:28.426
YEAH,
IT'S A LITTLE SHOWY.IT'S A LOTSHOWY.

11:28.470 --> 11:30.341
AND WHAT'S A ROOFTOP FULL
OF BEES COMPARED TO SOMEONE

11:30.385 --> 11:31.821
WHO CAN CATCH HER
WHEN SHE FALLS?

11:31.865 --> 11:33.170
I CAN'T CATCH HER,
EMERSON.

11:33.214 --> 11:34.694
CAN'T SUCK ON HER TOES,
NEITHER.

11:35.869 --> 11:38.480
SOME WOMEN LIKE THAT.

11:38.523 --> 11:41.352
Narrator:
BRADAN CADEN'S WIFE, BECKY,

11:41.396 --> 11:44.312
BELIEVED HER HUSBAND
WAS NOTSUICIDAL

11:44.355 --> 11:46.531
AND WAS, IN FACT, A HAPPY MAN.

11:46.575 --> 11:48.751
HE WAS A HAPPY MAN.

11:48.795 --> 11:51.188
THESE INSURANCE PEOPLE
MAKING ASSUMPTIONS

11:51.232 --> 11:53.321
ABOUT A PERSON'S
DISPOSITION --

11:53.364 --> 11:54.539
ONE SHOULD NEVER ASSUME.

11:54.583 --> 11:55.889
AN INSURANCE AGENT
CAN'T SPEAK

11:55.932 --> 11:57.499
TO THE DECEASED'S
STATE OF MIND.

11:57.542 --> 11:59.980
THEY DIDN'T KNOW THE DECEASED.
YOUDID.

12:00.023 --> 12:02.852
PARDON ME. I COULDN'T HELP
BUT OVERHEAR YOUR CONVERSATION.

12:02.896 --> 12:04.549
I BELIEVE
I COULD BE HELPFUL.

12:04.593 --> 12:06.290
MAY I HAVE A WORD WITH YOU?

12:09.903 --> 12:12.296
WHY ARE YOU BOTHERING
THIS POOR WOMAN?

12:12.340 --> 12:15.038
YOU AND THAT WHITE BOY GOT
SOME KIND OF SHIFTY GOING ON?

12:15.082 --> 12:18.476
I DON'T KNOW WHAT,
BUT YOU'RE SHIFTY.

12:18.520 --> 12:20.478
I'M HERE AS A CONCERNED CITIZEN
OF THE WORLD.

12:20.522 --> 12:22.654
YOU MAKING A DIME,
CONCERNED CITIZEN?

12:22.698 --> 12:24.569
MAYBE ONE OR TWO
TO RUB TOGETHER.

12:24.613 --> 12:29.052
WELL, THEN, FLIES LAND ON ME,
THEY PAY RENT.

12:33.056 --> 12:34.057
[ CHUCKLES ]

12:35.406 --> 12:38.801
[ CLEARS THROAT ]
EXCUSE ME. I'M J-JUST GONNA...

12:45.634 --> 12:47.070
[ WATCH TICKING ]

12:48.028 --> 12:49.377
HELLO.

12:49.420 --> 12:50.900
ARE YOU THE FELLOW
THAT JUMPED ON MY PLANE?

12:50.944 --> 12:53.207
NO. A FELLOW JUMPED
ON YOUR PLANE?

12:53.250 --> 12:54.469
I WAS HIJACKED.

12:54.512 --> 12:55.731
IS THAT WHY
YOUR PLANE CRASHED?

12:55.775 --> 12:57.994
OH, YES, SIRREE.

12:58.038 --> 12:59.430
MR. CADEN.

12:59.474 --> 13:02.042
I WAS DUSTING SOYBEANS,
OR GETTING READY TO,

13:02.085 --> 13:05.088
AND DIPPY IN A PRISON-ORANGE
JUMPSUIT CLIMBED ABOARD.

13:05.132 --> 13:07.047
DIPPY WAS ON BOARD
WHEN YOUR PLANE CRASHED?

13:07.090 --> 13:09.397
BUT YOU WERE THE ONLY DEAD
DIPPY -- BODY -- THEY FOUND.

13:09.440 --> 13:11.181
THEN DIPPY'S NOT DEAD.
LUCKY HIM.

13:11.225 --> 13:13.227
[ DOOR OPENS ]

13:14.750 --> 13:16.099
WHAT IN THE HELL?

13:16.143 --> 13:17.274
THE PLANE WAS HIJACKED.

13:17.318 --> 13:18.798
HOW'D YOU COME BY THAT?

13:18.841 --> 13:22.845
DNA-ish.

13:27.676 --> 13:28.590
Narrator: OLIVE SNOOK
CAME TO COEUR d'COEURS

13:28.633 --> 13:30.374
ON A WING AND A PRAYER.

13:30.418 --> 13:33.421
WITH A GILDED CAGE HOUSING
THE MONOWINGED BIRD IN ONE HAND

13:33.464 --> 13:35.205
AND A PIE BOX IN THE OTHER,

13:35.249 --> 13:37.860
SHE SET OUT TO EXPOSE
CHARLOTTE CHARLES,

13:37.904 --> 13:41.821
ALSO KNOWN AS "CHUCK,"
AS A FAKER OF DEATHS.

13:44.127 --> 13:47.783
Lily: MM-HMM.
IT'S A CARRIER PIGEON.

13:47.827 --> 13:49.263
DISEASES OR MESSAGES?

13:49.306 --> 13:50.525
[ PIGEON COOING ]

13:50.568 --> 13:52.266
BOTH.

13:52.309 --> 13:54.877
A BIRD WITH GOSSIP.
HOW EXCITING.

13:54.921 --> 13:57.924
DO YOU OPEN
OTHER PEOPLE'S MAIL?

13:57.967 --> 13:59.708
WELL, WHO'S THE PEOPLE
AND HOW HARD IS IT TO OPEN?

13:59.751 --> 14:01.405
[ LAUGHS ]

14:01.449 --> 14:03.103
I DON'T KNOW WHERE
THAT CAME FROM.

14:03.146 --> 14:04.800
WHAT'S GOTTEN INTO YOU?

14:04.844 --> 14:06.628
WHAT'S GOTTEN INTO YOU?

14:06.671 --> 14:08.412
Narrator: WHAT HAD GOTTEN
INTO BOTH OF THEM

14:08.456 --> 14:11.198
WAS THEIR NIECE'S
HOMEOPATHIC PIE.

14:11.241 --> 14:12.982
AS WITH ANY MOOD STABILIZER,

14:13.026 --> 14:15.811
MOODS WERE A BIT INCONSISTENT
AT THE START.

14:15.855 --> 14:17.552
DO YOU THINK
YOU CAN FIX HER?

14:17.595 --> 14:20.207
SHE'LL ONLY GO OUT THERE
AND GET HURT AGAIN.

14:20.250 --> 14:21.904
COYOTES WILL HAVE THEIR WAY
WITH HER.

14:21.948 --> 14:23.558
SHE WAS MEANT TO FLY.

14:23.601 --> 14:27.475
SHE NEEDS TO FULFILL HER DESTINY
AND DELIVER THAT MESSAGE.

14:27.518 --> 14:30.347
A BIRD THAT STALKS
DOWN HIS NARROW CAGE

14:30.391 --> 14:33.611
CAN SELDOM SEE THROUGH
HIS BARS OF RAGE!

14:33.655 --> 14:34.830
[ COUGHS ]

14:36.701 --> 14:38.616
IT WOULDN'T HURT TO TRY.

14:38.660 --> 14:40.836
THAT'S THE SPIRIT.

14:40.880 --> 14:43.970
AND ONCE WE FIX PIDGE,
WE CAN CELEBRATE --

14:44.013 --> 14:46.624
BY TAKING A TRIP
TO THE PIE HOLE.

14:46.668 --> 14:49.453
IT'S A NIFTY SPOT WITH LOTS
OF INTERESTING FOLKS.

14:49.497 --> 14:51.803
YOU NEVER KNOW
WHO YOU MIGHT RUN INTO.

14:51.847 --> 14:54.981
Narrator: WITH THAT, OLIVE SNOOK
SET HER PLAN IN MOTION.

14:55.024 --> 14:57.200
WHY WOULD WE GO OUT
FOR PIE

14:57.244 --> 14:59.115
WHEN YOU JUST
BROUGHT US ONE?

14:59.159 --> 15:02.336
I'LL THINK OF A REASON.

15:02.379 --> 15:04.381
Narrator:
WHILE OLIVE SNOOK CONSIDERED

15:04.425 --> 15:07.645
HOW TO GET LILY AND VIVIAN
OUT OF THEIR RUT,

15:07.689 --> 15:10.170
THE PIE MAKER WAS CONSIDERING
WORST-CASE SCENARIOS,

15:10.213 --> 15:11.998
NOT ONLY FOR A ROGUE HIJACKER,

15:12.041 --> 15:14.739
WHO HE HAD BEEN HIRED
TO FIND BY BECKY CADEN,

15:14.783 --> 15:17.220
BUT FOR CHUCK AND THE MAN
WHO CAUGHT HER

15:17.264 --> 15:19.570
IN A WAY THE PIE MAKER
NEVER COULD.

15:19.614 --> 15:21.529
THEY'RE NOT HERE.
THIS IS BAD.

15:21.572 --> 15:23.270
WELL, MAYBE THEY WENT
FOR A STROLL.

15:23.313 --> 15:24.836
THAT WOULD NOT
MAKE IT BETTER.

15:24.880 --> 15:26.795
WELL, WHAT'S WORSE --

15:26.838 --> 15:28.362
THE TWO OF THEM
LOCKED UP IN THE TRUNK
OF A HIJACKER'S CAR

15:28.405 --> 15:30.016
OR SIPPING MIMOSAS
IN A HOTEL ROOM?

15:30.059 --> 15:32.714
I'M NOT A FAN
OF EITHER SCENARIO,
AND WHAT'S THAT SMELL?

15:32.757 --> 15:34.368
I THOUGHT IT MIGHT BE
YOUR COLOGNE.

15:34.411 --> 15:35.673
WHO WEARS COLOGNE?

15:35.717 --> 15:38.894
IWEAR COLOGNE!

15:38.938 --> 15:41.723
[ SCOFFS ]
LOOK.

15:41.766 --> 15:44.421
THEY HAD COFFEE.

15:44.465 --> 15:45.727
OHH!

15:45.770 --> 15:48.208
THERE'S SOMETHING BAD
IN THERE.

15:51.515 --> 15:53.517
AAH!
MNH-MNH!

15:53.561 --> 15:54.866
IS THAT THE HIJACKER?

15:54.910 --> 15:56.781
WHAT KIND OF FOOL HIJACKER
HIDES HIMSELF

15:56.825 --> 15:59.306
IN A DAMN COFFEE TABLE?

16:04.354 --> 16:06.574
OW! OHH!

16:06.617 --> 16:08.228
DAMN GOUT.

16:08.271 --> 16:10.926
AAH, I'M SO CRAMPED, I FEEL LIKE
I'M STUFFED IN A TRUNK.

16:10.970 --> 16:12.493
YOU ARESTUFFED
IN A TRUNK.

16:12.536 --> 16:14.234
DON'T CONTRADICT AN OLD MAN.
IT'S DISRESPECTFUL.

16:14.277 --> 16:15.931
DID YOU HIJACK THAT PLANE?

16:15.975 --> 16:18.151
WHAT PLANE?
OH, HELL'S FIRE.

16:18.194 --> 16:19.761
THAT THING FLEW
INTO MY APARTMENT!

16:19.804 --> 16:21.415
THIS IS YOUR APARTMENT?

16:21.458 --> 16:22.938
WHAT'D I JUST SAY?

16:22.982 --> 16:25.941
THERE I WAS,
ENJOYING MY DAILY PRUNES

16:25.985 --> 16:29.031
AND THE PSYLLIUM POWDER
AND HOPING FOR THE BEST.

16:29.075 --> 16:31.207
AND SUDDENLY, I SEE THAT THING
FLYING AT ME.

16:31.251 --> 16:33.949
IF THIS IS YOUR APARTMENT,
THEN WHO IS CONRAD?

16:33.993 --> 16:36.038
WHAT IS THIS --
THE IDIOT BRIGADE?

16:36.082 --> 16:37.953
[ Sing-song voice ] HELLO.

16:37.997 --> 16:39.824
OH.

16:43.306 --> 16:44.829
DO YOU LIKE PIE?

16:44.873 --> 16:46.875
IT WOULD BE CRIMINAL
NOT TO LIKE PIE.

16:48.703 --> 16:53.403
EVERYTHING I AM,
EVERYTHING I WAS,

16:53.447 --> 16:55.318
EVERYTHING
THAT REPRESENTED ME

16:55.362 --> 16:57.277
AS A HUMAN BEING
WAS IN THERE.

16:57.320 --> 16:58.974
I HAVE TO START OVER.

16:59.018 --> 17:01.542
I LOST EVERYTHING ONCE.
AND YOU KNOW WHAT?

17:01.585 --> 17:02.804
DID A PLANE FLY
INTO YOUR LIVING ROOM?

17:02.847 --> 17:04.371
NO.
WELL, WAS IT ARSON?

17:04.414 --> 17:05.850
NO, IT WAS SOMETHING ELSE,

17:05.894 --> 17:07.287
BUT I FELT A QUEER THRILL
OF OPPORTUNITY.

17:07.330 --> 17:09.202
TO GET NEW STUFF?

17:09.245 --> 17:11.682
TO LET GO OF EVERYTHING ABOUT ME
THAT I DIDN'T LIKE

17:11.726 --> 17:14.076
AND TO HOLD ONTO EVERYTHING
ABOUT ME THAT I DID.

17:14.120 --> 17:15.512
WELL, I'VE JUST MET YOU,

17:15.556 --> 17:17.514
BUT I...CAN'T IMAGINE
ANYTHING ABOUT YOU

17:17.558 --> 17:18.863
THAT ISN'T SOMETHING
TO LIKE.

17:20.648 --> 17:24.913
Narrator:
CHUCK'S FIRST THOUGHT WAS TO
QUICKLY PULL HER HAND AWAY.

17:24.956 --> 17:27.046
HER SECOND THOUGHT
WAS HOW NICE IT FELT

17:27.089 --> 17:29.657
TO HAVE SOMEONEHOLD HER HAND.

17:30.701 --> 17:33.095
OH. [ CHUCKLES ]
SORRY.

17:33.139 --> 17:35.706
WAS THAT YOUR BOYFRIEND
BACK THERE,

17:35.750 --> 17:38.840
THE ONE WHO TOOK A STEP BACK
TO LET YOU FALL?

17:38.883 --> 17:40.755
HE DIDN'T LET ME FALL.

17:40.798 --> 17:43.149
IT WAS ACTUALLY
A VERY AFFECTIONATE
GESTURE IN CONTEXT.

17:43.192 --> 17:46.326
Narrator: IF IT WAS ONLY
THE PIE MAKER'S HAND.

17:46.369 --> 17:49.242
CAN I ASK YOU
A SMALL FAVOR?

17:50.852 --> 17:52.984
WOULD YOU HOLD MY HAND
JUST FOR A MOMENT,

17:53.028 --> 17:54.725
BUT DON'T SAY ANYTHING?

17:54.769 --> 17:56.249
AND I'M GONNA CLOSE
MY EYES.

17:57.685 --> 17:59.208
ALL RIGHT.

18:14.615 --> 18:16.138
Narrator: IN THAT MOMENT,

18:16.182 --> 18:19.402
CHUCK WASHOLDING
THE PIE MAKER'S HAND...

18:21.665 --> 18:23.189
...IF ONLY BY PROXY.

18:23.232 --> 18:24.233
[ CLEARS THROAT ]

18:28.324 --> 18:31.545
Narrator: IT WAS THE PROXY
THAT CONCERNED THE PIE MAKER.

18:31.588 --> 18:33.764
I GOT TO PEE.

18:35.418 --> 18:36.202
HOW DID IT GO?

18:36.245 --> 18:37.464
WHERE DID HE GO?

18:37.507 --> 18:40.206
CONRAD? HE WAS GOING
TO THE BATHROOM.

18:40.249 --> 18:42.860
HE'S NOT CONRAD.
HE'S THE HIJACKER.

18:44.123 --> 18:46.299
AND HE'S GOING TO THE BATHROOM
IN MY KITCHEN.

18:46.342 --> 18:48.170
BOY, YOU MISS ONE TRIP
TO THE MORGUE...

18:57.223 --> 18:59.181
[ GRUNTING ]

18:59.225 --> 19:01.052
[ POP! ]OHH!

19:01.096 --> 19:02.358
OHH!

19:09.409 --> 19:12.629
IS THIS THE HAND
YOU WERE HOLDING?

19:20.071 --> 19:21.943
WELL, HE'S A GREAT BIG FIBBER,
THEN, ISN'T HE?

19:21.986 --> 19:24.075
A GREAT BIG FIBBER,
WHOSE HAND YOU WERE HOLDING.

19:24.119 --> 19:25.207
WHAT'S THAT ABOUT?

19:25.251 --> 19:27.209
I WAS --
I-IF YOU MUST KNOW...

19:27.253 --> 19:28.732
[ BREATHES DEEPLY ]

19:28.776 --> 19:30.604
I WAS PRETENDING I WAS HOLDING
YOURHAND.

19:30.647 --> 19:32.214
IS THAT SUPPOSED
TO MAKE ME FEEL BETTER?

19:32.258 --> 19:34.738
WELL...YEAH.

19:34.782 --> 19:36.740
OH, WELL, ON ONE HAND,
IT DOES MAKE ME FEEL BETTER.

19:36.784 --> 19:38.960
ON THE OTHER HAND -- THE HAND
YOU WERE HOLDING -- IT DOESN'T.

19:39.003 --> 19:40.918
NED,
HE'S AN ESCAPED CONVICT.

19:40.962 --> 19:42.442
YOU DIDN'T KNOW THAT
WHEN YOU HELD HIS HAND.

19:42.485 --> 19:43.399
AND P.S., NOT ONLY
IS HE AN ESCAPED CONVICT --

19:43.443 --> 19:44.705
HE'S ALSO A HIJACKER

19:44.748 --> 19:46.402
WHO'S PREVENTED
THOUSANDS OF CROPS

19:46.446 --> 19:48.187
FROM BEING
AERIALLY FERTILIZED.

19:48.230 --> 19:50.972
AND HE STUFFED A SURLY OLD
DEAD GUY IN A TRUNK.

19:51.015 --> 19:52.626
I'M NOT SAYING
THAT HE ISN'T GUILTY,

19:52.669 --> 19:54.018
AND I'M NOT SAYING
THAT I AM.

19:54.062 --> 19:55.846
I'M JUST SAYING
THAT IT'S NOT ABOUT HIM.

19:55.890 --> 19:57.065
NO, IT'S ABOUT OUR CLIENT,

19:57.108 --> 19:58.675
BECKY CADEN,
WIFE OF BRADAN CADEN,

19:58.719 --> 20:00.286
THE WOMAN
YOUR HANDYMAN WIDOWED

20:00.329 --> 20:02.766
WHEN HE DECIDED TO CROP-DUST
SOMEONE'S LIVING ROOM.

20:02.810 --> 20:04.246
DID YOU CATCH HIM?

20:04.290 --> 20:06.161
[ SIGHS ] THAT ONE-ARMED BITCH
WAS SPEEDY.

20:06.205 --> 20:08.424
BUT I CHECKED IN WITH MY PEOPLE
AT THE PRISON.

20:08.468 --> 20:10.470
YOU GOT "PEOPLE"?
THAT'S SO NEAT.

20:10.513 --> 20:11.558
DID YOU FIND OUT
ANYTHING GOOD?

20:11.601 --> 20:12.820
YES.

20:12.863 --> 20:14.474
AND WE'RE GONNA NEED SHOVELS.

20:16.693 --> 20:19.566
Narrator: EMERSON COD
HAD LEARNED THREE THINGS --

20:19.609 --> 20:22.177
FIRST, THE MAN THEY KNEW
AS CONRAD FITCH

20:22.221 --> 20:25.528
WAS ACTUALLY ONE
LEMUEL WINEGARD,

20:25.572 --> 20:27.138
A LOW-LEVEL EMPLOYEE

20:27.182 --> 20:29.793
OF A COMPANY CALLED
ORNAN ENERGY.

20:29.837 --> 20:33.667
SECOND, ORNAN WAS
AN ENERGY-BASED CORPORATION

20:33.710 --> 20:35.625
KNOWN FOR SEVERAL TYPES
OF TRADING --

20:35.669 --> 20:40.587
PLASTICS, STEEL, AND INSIDER.

20:40.630 --> 20:42.937
THE LATTER COST LEMUEL
HIS RIGHT HAND.

20:42.980 --> 20:44.591
AAH!

20:44.634 --> 20:46.157
AAH!

20:46.201 --> 20:49.509
Narrator:
IT ALSO COST HIM HIS FREEDOM.

20:49.552 --> 20:52.207
THIRD, DURING HIS INCARCERATION,

20:52.251 --> 20:55.297
LEMUEL BECAME KNOWN
AS "LEFTY LEM,"

20:55.341 --> 20:58.996
A NAME GIVEN TO HIM
BY HIS CELLMATE, JACKSON LUCAS,

20:59.040 --> 21:00.737
AN INFAMOUS DIAMOND THIEF,

21:00.781 --> 21:03.436
WHOSE FINAL ESCAPADE
RESULTED IN A BURIED TREASURE

21:03.479 --> 21:05.916
THAT WAS NEVER RECOVERED...

21:13.576 --> 21:15.361
...EVEN AFTER HE DIED.

21:15.404 --> 21:19.060
HE ENDED UP IN A PRISON
GRAVEYARD WITH HIS SECRET.

21:19.103 --> 21:22.150
OH, SO LEFTY LEM WAS
A WHITE-COLLAR CRIMINAL.

21:22.193 --> 21:23.630
THAT MAKES MUCH MORE SENSE.

21:23.673 --> 21:26.285
OH, YEAH, THANK YOU.

21:26.328 --> 21:28.374
GONNA GET PAID ONCE
BY THE PILOT'S WIDOW

21:28.417 --> 21:31.072
WHEN WE PROVE HER HUSBAND'S
DEATH WASN'T A SUICIDE --

21:31.115 --> 21:33.379
DEAD BODIES ALWAYS LEAD
TO PAYDAYS.

21:33.422 --> 21:36.207
YEAH, YEAH,
"VODKA IN THE FREEZER."

21:36.251 --> 21:37.687
GONNA GET PAID TWICE
BY THE FEDS

21:37.731 --> 21:39.341
WHEN THEY GIVE US THE REWARD
FOR KICKING LEFTY'S ASS

21:39.385 --> 21:40.734
BACK TO THE CLINK,
WHERE HE BELONGS.

21:40.777 --> 21:42.344
LOOKING FORWARD TO THAT.

21:42.388 --> 21:43.780
AND GONNA GET PAID THRICE

21:43.824 --> 21:45.826
BY FINDING JACKSON'S
BURIED BOOTY.

21:45.869 --> 21:47.262
[ CHUCKLES ]

21:47.306 --> 21:48.263
HEY!

21:48.307 --> 21:50.613
[ CLANK! ]
HEY.

21:52.789 --> 21:54.791
COME TO PAPA.

22:00.014 --> 22:01.929
Ned: WAIT. YOU MIGHT WANT
TO AVERT YOUR EYES.

22:01.972 --> 22:04.192
THERE'S A GOOD CHANCE
HE'LL BE ON THE DEWY SIDE.

22:04.235 --> 22:06.020
DAMN. I HATEDEWY.

22:06.063 --> 22:08.327
ARE YOU MAD AT ME?

22:08.370 --> 22:09.893
WHY WOULD I BE MAD?

22:09.937 --> 22:12.766
FOR HOLDING SOMEONE'S HAND
THAT WASN'T YOURS.

22:12.809 --> 22:15.290
SERIOUSLY,
IN A PRISON GRAVEYARD --

22:15.334 --> 22:17.248
THAT'S WHERE Y'ALL ARE GONNA
HAVE THIS CONVERSATION?

22:17.292 --> 22:21.470
YOU SHOULD, UH,
BREATHE THROUGH YOUR MOUTHS.

22:24.168 --> 22:27.128
[ COFFIN LID CLATTERS ]

22:27.171 --> 22:28.869
[ EXHALES DEEPLY ]

22:28.912 --> 22:30.958
I WOULD HAVE PREFERRED
A LITTLE MORE EYEBALL.

22:31.001 --> 22:32.394
Emerson: JUST TOUCH
THE DAMN THING.

22:32.438 --> 22:34.309
NO, WAIT.FOR WHAT?

22:34.353 --> 22:36.311
A LITTLE DIGNITY.

22:40.010 --> 22:41.360
[ CHUCKLES ]

22:41.403 --> 22:43.231
THANKS.

22:45.929 --> 22:48.236
[ WATCH TICKING ]

22:48.279 --> 22:51.718
I CAN'T SEE ANYTHING!
AM I BLIND?

22:51.761 --> 22:52.675
THE GOOD NEWS IS,
YOU'RE NOT BLIND.

22:52.719 --> 22:54.198
BAD NEWS IS,
YOU'RE DEAD.

22:54.242 --> 22:56.287
MAKES BLIND SEEM LIKE A WALK
IN THE PARK, DOESN'T IT?

22:56.331 --> 22:58.333
WHERE'D YOU BURY
YOUR LOOT, JACK?

22:58.377 --> 23:01.292
HA!
WHY SHOULD I TELL YOU?

23:01.336 --> 23:04.557
GOOD KARMA.
IT'S LIKE CURRENCY
IN THE AFTERLIFE.

23:04.600 --> 23:08.430
IN THE OLD WINDMILL
ON THE VonRoenn FARM,

23:08.474 --> 23:10.693
AT THE BOTTOM
OF THE STAIRS.

23:10.737 --> 23:12.086
HOW MUCH THAT WORTH?

23:12.129 --> 23:14.175
PLENTY.
ASK HIM ABOUT LEFTY.

23:14.218 --> 23:15.437
DID YOU TELL HIM
WHERE YOU BURIED IT?

23:15.481 --> 23:17.483
[ BREATHES DEEPLY ]
OF COURSE I DID.

23:17.526 --> 23:19.180
OWED HIM THAT MUCH.

23:19.223 --> 23:21.008
W-WHAT DID YOU
OWE HIM FOR?

23:21.051 --> 23:22.966
KEEPING THE FIRE ALIVE.

23:24.446 --> 23:27.144
ALL RIGHT,
WE GOT A WINDMILL TO FIND.

23:27.188 --> 23:29.495
Narrator: CHUCK'S FIRE
MAY NOT BE ALIVE,

23:29.538 --> 23:32.846
AS FAR AS HER AUNTS LILY
AND VIVIAN WERE CONCERNED,

23:32.889 --> 23:35.152
BUT OLIVE WAS DOING HER BEST
TO REIGNITE IT.

23:35.196 --> 23:36.502
BRACKETS.

23:36.545 --> 23:37.981
BRACKETS.

23:38.025 --> 23:39.679
RIBBON.

23:39.722 --> 23:40.593
RIBBON.

23:40.636 --> 23:42.203
BEJEWELER.

23:42.246 --> 23:43.726
BEJEWELER.

23:46.033 --> 23:47.034
CAN I DO ONE?

23:47.077 --> 23:48.992
MAYBE THE LAST ONE.

23:49.036 --> 23:52.605
IF YOU LIKE, WE COULD
BEJEWEL PIDGE'S BIRDHOUSE
WHEN WE'RE DONE.

23:52.648 --> 23:54.520
PIDGE'S HOUSE
IS ONLY TEMPORARY.

23:54.563 --> 23:57.305
NO SENSE IN BEJEWELING AN EMPTY
HOME, IS THERE, PIDGE?

23:57.348 --> 23:59.873
THERE'S SOMETHING SO SAD
ABOUT AN EMPTY BIRDHOUSE.

23:59.916 --> 24:02.702
WHEN ONE OF OUR BIRDS DIES,
WE TAXIDERM IT IMMEDIATELY --

24:02.745 --> 24:04.486
PUT IT RIGHT BACK
ON ITS PERCH.

24:04.530 --> 24:07.141
VIVIAN DOES WONDERS
WITH SAND AND THREAD.

24:07.184 --> 24:08.490
AND LITTLE MARBLE EYES.

24:08.534 --> 24:10.405
IT'S LIKE OUR BIRDS
NEVER LEFT US AT ALL.

24:10.449 --> 24:13.800
YOU CAN'T PUT EVERYTHING
BACK ON ITS PERCH.

24:13.843 --> 24:16.193
IT MUST HAVE BEEN
ALL KINDS OF HORRIBLE FOR YOU

24:16.237 --> 24:17.804
WHEN CHARLOTTE LEFT.

24:17.847 --> 24:20.197
SHE DIDN'T LEAVE.

24:20.241 --> 24:21.895
SHE DIED.

24:21.938 --> 24:25.420
AND NO AMOUNT OF SAND OR THREAD
OR LITTLE MARBLE EYES

24:25.464 --> 24:27.074
WILL EVER BRING HERBACK.

24:27.117 --> 24:30.425
Narrator: BUT OLIVE DIDN'T NEED
SAND OR THREAD

24:30.469 --> 24:32.819
OR LITTLE MARBLE EYES
TO BRING CHUCK BACK.

24:32.862 --> 24:35.561
SHE NEEDED A CONFLUENCE
OF EVENTS.

24:35.604 --> 24:37.650
WING.

24:37.693 --> 24:40.304
Narrator:
AND SHE WAS ABOUT TO GET ONE.

24:43.003 --> 24:44.178
WING.

24:44.221 --> 24:45.919
[ COOING ]

24:45.962 --> 24:47.921
CAN I DO THE LAST BEJEWEL?

24:47.964 --> 24:50.706
[ SNAPS ]I ALREADY DID IT.

24:50.750 --> 24:52.403
[ COOING ]

24:52.447 --> 24:55.450
OH!

24:55.494 --> 24:59.280
WHAT DO YOU THINK, PIDGE?

24:59.323 --> 25:01.978
Narrator: AND WHILE OLIVE,
THE AUNTS, AND PIDGE

25:02.022 --> 25:05.199
LOOKED FORWARD TO THE NEXT STEP
IN THEIR JOURNEY,

25:05.242 --> 25:10.378
ANOTHER JOURNEY HAD REACHED
A DEAD END.

25:10.421 --> 25:11.901
IS SHE DEAD?

25:11.945 --> 25:15.688
LEFTY LEM HAS OFFICIALLY
TAKEN THE LEAD.

25:19.822 --> 25:21.258
DO YOU THINK FAKE CONRAD
KILLED HER?

25:21.302 --> 25:22.869
OCKHAM'S RAZOR --
ALL THINGS BEING EQUAL,

25:22.912 --> 25:25.088
THE SIMPLEST SOLUTION
TENDS TO BE THE BEST ONE.

25:25.132 --> 25:26.829
I USED TO BELIEVE THAT
UNTIL YOU BROUGHT ME
BACK FROM THE DEAD --

25:26.873 --> 25:29.049
KIND OF SCREWS THE THEORY.

25:29.092 --> 25:30.920
[ WATCH TICKING ]

25:38.841 --> 25:41.888
MAYBE YOUR FINGER
NEEDS A NEW BATTERY.

25:41.931 --> 25:43.237
HERE, LET ME TRY.

25:43.280 --> 25:45.239
[ SNORTS ] OW!

25:45.282 --> 25:47.197
HE DID IT.HE DID IT.

25:47.241 --> 25:51.027
OH! I MUST HAVE DOZED OFF AGAIN.
UH, CAN I HELP YOU?

25:51.071 --> 25:54.422
WE'RE LOOKING FOR A WINDMILL,
A VonRoenn-VARIETY WINDMILL.

25:54.465 --> 25:56.293
OH, THAT'S FUNNY.

25:56.337 --> 25:59.601
A YOUNG MAN WAS JUST IN HERE,
ASKING ABOUT THE VonRoenn MILL.

25:59.645 --> 26:01.647
HE DIDN'T HAPPEN TO HAVE
ONE ARM, DID HE?

26:01.690 --> 26:02.996
AS A MATTER OF FACT, HE DID.

26:03.039 --> 26:04.737
[ Sneezing ] OCKHAM'S!BLESS YOU.

26:04.780 --> 26:05.999
THANK YOU.

26:06.042 --> 26:08.088
THE WINDMILL --
WHAT HAPPENED TO IT?

26:08.131 --> 26:09.742
RAZED, WRECKED,
REBUILT, REMOVED?

26:09.785 --> 26:13.310
RETIRED.
NO FARM, NO USE.

26:13.354 --> 26:16.444
GOT SHIPPED OFF TO "NARM"
SOME 20 YEARS AGO.

26:16.487 --> 26:18.141
WHY DID THEY SEND IT
TO NAM?

26:18.185 --> 26:20.187
DID THE VIETNAMESE
NEED WINDMILLS?

26:20.230 --> 26:22.624
N.A.R.M. -- NATIONAL AREA
OF RETIRED MILLS.

26:22.668 --> 26:25.105
THE VonRoenn MILL
HAS BEEN PRESERVED

26:25.148 --> 26:27.760
FOR AN HISTORICAL LANDMARK.

26:27.803 --> 26:31.024
I HAVE A MAP HERE.
[ CHUCKLES ]

26:34.897 --> 26:38.205
NOW, THAT'S NARCOLEPTIC.
NECROPHILIAC'S THE OTHER ONE.

26:38.248 --> 26:39.772
YEAH.

26:39.815 --> 26:41.687
Narrator:
ARMED WITH A NEW PLAN,

26:41.730 --> 26:44.907
THE PIE MAKER AND ASSOCIATES
LEFT THE NARCOLEPTIC CURATOR

26:44.951 --> 26:46.474
TO HER DREAMS.

26:46.517 --> 26:48.650
MEANWHILE,
BACK IN COEUR d'COEURS,

26:48.694 --> 26:51.914
A TINY FRIEND WAS PLANNING
HER OWN ESCAPE.

26:51.958 --> 26:55.657
OLIVE'S DISDAIN FOR CHUCK
WAS SPLIT IN TWO --

26:55.701 --> 26:57.703
ONE FOR STEALING
THE PIE MAKER'S HEART

26:57.746 --> 26:59.792
AND THE OTHER
FOR BREAKING THE AUNTS'.

26:59.835 --> 27:01.924
YOU KNOW YOU WANT TO READ
PIDGE'S MESSAGE.

27:01.968 --> 27:04.710
LILY WOULD BE
SO DISPLEASED.

27:06.102 --> 27:08.322
THERE WAS AN INCIDENT.

27:08.365 --> 27:10.585
I READ SOMETHING
THAT I SHOULDN'T HAVE,

27:10.629 --> 27:14.458
AND THEN LIFE
WENT HORRIBLY AWRY.

27:14.502 --> 27:15.764
LILY NEVER FORGAVE ME.

27:15.808 --> 27:18.724
SHE SAID SHE DID,
BUT SHE DIDN'T.

27:18.767 --> 27:22.815
WOW. NOW I'M MORE INTERESTED
IN THATSTORY.

27:22.858 --> 27:25.339
LET'S PUT PIDGE BACK
INTO HER HOUSE.

27:25.382 --> 27:28.690
PIDGE HAS LEFT THE BUILDING.
I'M SORRY.

27:28.734 --> 27:32.259
I'M SORRY HER EMPTY BIRDHOUSE
MAKES YOU SAD.

27:32.302 --> 27:35.436
MAYBE YOU COULD FILL IT
WITH ALL YOUR CHARLOTTE SADNESS

27:35.479 --> 27:38.178
AND HANG IT IN A SPECIAL PLACE
IN YOUR SOUL.

27:38.221 --> 27:40.659
THAT'S AN AWFULLY SAD
BIRDHOUSE

27:40.702 --> 27:43.096
TO HAVE HANGING
IN ONE'S SOUL.

27:43.139 --> 27:45.315
HANG IT SOMEPLACE
YOU DON'T HAVE TO SEEIT.

27:45.359 --> 27:48.362
IT WON'T ALWAYS BE SAD.

27:48.405 --> 27:51.321
IT'LL BE THE HAPPIEST LITTLE
BIRDHOUSE WHEN YOU'RE READY.

27:51.365 --> 27:54.281
MAKE A LITTLE BIRDHOUSE
IN YOUR SOUL.

27:54.324 --> 27:56.196
DON'T ENCOURAGE HER.

27:57.588 --> 28:00.722
I THINK SHE LOOKS DIVINE.

28:00.766 --> 28:02.681
[ COOING ]

28:09.557 --> 28:10.732
SON OF A BITCH.

28:10.776 --> 28:13.213
WAIT! YOU FORGOT YOUR MESSAGE!
PIDGE!

28:13.256 --> 28:16.782
PIDGE, WAIT!
YOU FORGOT YOUR MESSAGE!

28:16.825 --> 28:20.524
Narrator: AS THE AUNTS WATCHED
OLIVE SCREAM FOR HELP...

28:20.568 --> 28:21.700
PIDGE!

28:21.743 --> 28:23.397
HELP ME! PIDGE!

28:23.440 --> 28:25.747
Narrator: ...THEY CONSIDERED
THEIR OWN BIRDCAGE

28:25.791 --> 28:28.881
AND WONDERED IF THEY WERE READY
TO LEAVE IT BEHIND.

28:28.924 --> 28:32.406
A FEW MILES AWAY...

28:32.449 --> 28:35.278
LOOKING OUT ACROSS THE FIELDS,

28:35.322 --> 28:39.239
A BEAUTIFUL WOMAN NAMED ELSITA
WAITED FOR THE MAN SHE LOVED

28:39.282 --> 28:41.067
TO MAKE HER HEART COMPLETE.

28:41.110 --> 28:42.764
[ KNOCK ON DOOR ]

28:42.808 --> 28:47.247
LITTLE DID SHE KNOW LEFTY LEM
WAS ALREADY ON HIS WAY.

28:47.290 --> 28:49.075
WHAT THE HELL DO YOUWANT?

28:49.118 --> 28:52.513
I'M FROM THE PAPEN COUNTY
HISTORICAL SOCIETY.

28:52.556 --> 28:54.297
WE'D LIKE TO PHOTOGRAPH
THESE PREMISES

28:54.341 --> 28:56.169
FOR OUR 87th ANNUAL
"MILLS OF THE WIND"

28:56.212 --> 28:57.823
PAPEN COUNTY COLLECTOR'S
CALENDAR.

28:57.866 --> 28:59.825
WHERE'S YOUR CAMERA?

28:59.868 --> 29:02.697
IT'S IN THE CAR.

29:02.741 --> 29:04.525
YOU'RE LYING.

29:04.568 --> 29:05.831
BUT I'M BORED.

29:22.848 --> 29:23.936
Olive and Vivian:
♪ I'M YOUR ONLY FRIEND

29:23.979 --> 29:25.328
♪ I'M NOT YOUR ONLY FRIEND

29:25.372 --> 29:27.374
♪ BUT I'M A LITTLE
GLOWING FRIEND ♪

29:27.417 --> 29:30.681
♪ BUT, REALLY, I'M NOT
ACTUALLY YOUR FRIEND ♪

29:30.725 --> 29:32.205
♪ BUT I AM

29:32.248 --> 29:34.555
♪ BLUE CANARY IN THE OUTLET
BY THE LIGHT SWITCH ♪

29:34.598 --> 29:37.210
♪ WHO WATCHES OVER YOU

29:37.253 --> 29:40.169
♪ MAKE A LITTLE BIRDHOUSE
IN YOUR SOUL ♪

29:40.213 --> 29:42.258
♪ NOT TO PUT TOO FINE
A POINT ON IT ♪

29:42.302 --> 29:45.087
♪ SAY I'M THE ONLY BEE
IN YOUR BONNET ♪

29:45.131 --> 29:51.224
♪ MAKE A LITTLE BIRDHOUSE
IN YOUR SOU-U-U-U-L ♪

29:51.267 --> 29:54.096
NEVER MIND THE SINGING.
KEEP YOUR EYE ON THAT BIRD.

29:54.140 --> 29:55.141
OH.

29:59.319 --> 30:00.799
YOU KNOW
WHAT OUR PROBLEM IS.

30:00.842 --> 30:02.626
IF YOU'RE REFERRING
TO THE TOUCHING THING,

30:02.670 --> 30:04.541
I SEE IT AS MORE OF AN OBSTACLE
THAN A PROBLEM.

30:04.585 --> 30:05.673
IT'S A PRETTY BIG
OBSTACLE.

30:05.716 --> 30:06.935
NOT COMPARED
TO OUR OTHER PROBLEMS.

30:06.979 --> 30:08.241
WE'VE GOT
"OTHER PROBLEMS"?

30:08.284 --> 30:09.633
I'M GONNA KILL MYSELF.

30:09.677 --> 30:11.853
THERE'S SO MUCH
I'M LEARNING ABOUT YOU.

30:11.897 --> 30:13.463
SUCH AS?

30:13.507 --> 30:14.856
YOU'RE ROMANTIC.

30:14.900 --> 30:16.292
WHEN THE MOOD STRIKES.

30:16.336 --> 30:17.467
AND YOU'RE JEALOUS
WHEN THE MOOD STRIKES.

30:17.511 --> 30:19.426
EVERYONE'S
A LITTLE JEALOUS.

30:19.469 --> 30:21.907
I MEAN, IF YOU'RE NOT
A LITTLE JEALOUS,
YOU'RE PROBABLY...

30:21.950 --> 30:24.300
[ EXHALES RAGGEDLY ]
CAN WE NOT TALK ABOUT THIS?

30:24.344 --> 30:26.476
THE ANSWER TO YOUR QUERY
IS "YES."

30:26.520 --> 30:28.217
NO, ACTUALLY,
I-I WANT TO TALK ABOUT THIS.

30:28.261 --> 30:30.263
I COULD LET IT GO, BUT LIKE
THE CAT, IT WILL COME BACK,

30:30.306 --> 30:32.047
WHICH I WOULDN'T CALL
ANNOYING,

30:32.091 --> 30:34.136
BUT THERE'S NO REALLY GREAT WAY
OF SAYING "HALF ANNOYING,"

30:34.180 --> 30:35.268
WHICH IT IS A LITTLE BIT.

30:35.311 --> 30:36.965
SEE?
ISN'T THIS NEAT?

30:37.009 --> 30:39.054
HERE WE WERE, THINKING ALL
WE HAD WAS ONE BIG PROBLEM,

30:39.098 --> 30:41.274
WHEN, IN ACTUAL FACT, WE HAVE
HUNDREDS OF LITTLE PROBLEMS

30:41.317 --> 30:43.885
THAT WE GOT TO SORT OUT
BEFORE WE EVEN GET TO
THE BIG PROBLEM,

30:43.929 --> 30:45.844
WHICH MEANS WE'RE LIKE
EVERYBODY ELSE IN THE WORLD.

30:45.887 --> 30:48.847
EXCEPT I STILL CAN'T
CATCH YOU.

30:51.197 --> 30:54.156
YEAH, WE TAKING TWO CARS
NEXT TIME.

30:54.200 --> 30:56.942
THAT'S A BIG AX.

30:56.985 --> 30:58.900
OH, I'M NOT GONNA HURT YOU.
I PROMISE.

30:58.944 --> 31:01.990
THIS IS, UH, JUST
A PRECAUTIONARY MEASURE.

31:02.034 --> 31:04.732
WOULDN'T IT BE EASIER
IF YOU PUT THE AX DOWN,

31:04.775 --> 31:05.951
THEN TIED THE ROPE?

31:12.218 --> 31:14.394
IT'S FUNNY -- YOU REALLY
ARE A ONE-ARMED BANDIT.

31:14.437 --> 31:16.091
YOUR NAME'S NOT McCLAPPING,
IS IT?

31:16.135 --> 31:18.441
AS IN "THE SOUND
OF ONE HAND"...
NO.

31:18.485 --> 31:20.922
'CAUSE NAMES ARE DESTINY.

31:20.966 --> 31:22.402
IF YOU THINK
"DWAYNE CLOGGIN"

31:22.445 --> 31:24.012
AIN'T GONNA GROW UP
TO BE A PLUMBER,

31:24.056 --> 31:25.884
THEN YOU JUST
THINK AGAIN.

31:25.927 --> 31:28.712
OH, NO, YOU DIDN'T USE BOWS
TO TIE ME UP, DID YOU?

31:28.756 --> 31:31.367
YOU TAKE A HOSTAGE
LIKE YOU TIE YOUR SNEAKERS.

31:31.411 --> 31:33.195
WHAT IS YOUR PROBLEM?

31:33.239 --> 31:35.894
WELL, I WAS BORN INTO
THE LIFE OF WINDMILLERY.

31:35.937 --> 31:37.591
[ KNOCKING ]

31:37.634 --> 31:39.636
ARE YOU GONNA LISTEN,
OR ARE YOU GONNA KEEP KNOCKING?

31:39.680 --> 31:40.986
I'M LISTENING.

31:41.029 --> 31:43.379
YOU WERE BORN INTO
THE LIFE OF WINDMILLERY.

31:43.423 --> 31:45.381
ALWAYS WAITING ON THE WIND
TO SHOW UP,

31:45.425 --> 31:47.906
SO YOU CAN START WORK,
AND I'M NO GOOD AT WAITING.

31:47.949 --> 31:49.646
I'M TIRED OF IT.

31:49.690 --> 31:53.259
YOU SURE IT WAS THE WIND
THAT YOU WERE A-WAITING FOR?

31:55.043 --> 31:56.740
DID YOU JUST SAY
"A-WAITING"?

31:56.784 --> 31:58.003
'CAUSE IF YOU ARE
MIMICKING ME,

31:58.046 --> 31:59.395
I WILL BE OUT
OF THESE GIRLY BOWS

31:59.439 --> 32:00.831
FASTER THAN A SNAKE
THROUGH WEEDS!

32:00.875 --> 32:02.921
I WASN'T THINKING,
AND I APOLOGIZE.

32:02.964 --> 32:05.575
IT'S JUST, WELL,
I HAVE A LOT ON MY MIND,

32:05.619 --> 32:07.316
AND I'M IN A BIT
OF A RUSH.

32:07.360 --> 32:09.710
OH, WHERE YOU RUSHING TO?

32:09.753 --> 32:13.714
WELL, I DON'T
REALLY KNOW YET.

32:13.757 --> 32:17.152
WELL, MAYBE YOU BETTER
FIGURE THAT OUT.

32:22.070 --> 32:23.942
GO BACK TO YOUR KNOCKING.
[ CLEARS THROAT ]

32:26.814 --> 32:29.338
[ KNOCKING ]

32:34.430 --> 32:37.738
COME ON, PIDGE!
YOU CAN DO IT!

32:37.781 --> 32:39.958
NOT EVEN A BREEZE
TO HELP POOR PIDGE,

32:40.001 --> 32:42.612
WHICH IS KIND OF IRONIC,
GIVEN THE SURROUNDINGS.

32:42.656 --> 32:44.310
PIDGE! COME ON!

32:44.353 --> 32:47.835
Narrator: THE PIGEON,
GROWING FATIGUED WITH EACH FLAP

32:47.878 --> 32:49.489
OF HER TAXIDERMIED WING,

32:49.532 --> 32:51.970
KNEW SOMETHING
THE OTHERS DID NOT.

32:52.013 --> 32:55.234
[ SQUAWKS ]HER JOURNEY WAS ALMOST COMPLETE.

32:55.277 --> 32:56.800
[ TIRES SCREECH ]

32:56.844 --> 32:58.106
OH.

32:58.150 --> 33:00.630
WHAT WAS THAT?

33:00.674 --> 33:01.980
[ COOING ]

33:02.023 --> 33:03.024
IT'S MY BIRD!

33:05.244 --> 33:06.985
[ GASPS ]

33:07.028 --> 33:08.987
[ COOING ]

33:09.030 --> 33:10.814
THAT'S MYBIRD.

33:10.858 --> 33:13.078
WHAT ARE YOU ON ABOUT?
IT'S MYBIRD.

33:13.121 --> 33:15.384
I'LL PROVE IT.
I WROTE THE NOTE.

33:15.428 --> 33:17.212
WHERE'S THE NOTE?

33:17.256 --> 33:18.474
Olive: HELLO?

33:18.518 --> 33:20.041
CAN I GET MY BIRD BACK,
PLEASE?

33:20.085 --> 33:21.434
YOURBIRD?  YOURBIRD?

33:21.477 --> 33:23.218
YES, MY BIRD.
SHE'S A CARRIER PIGEON.

33:23.262 --> 33:25.481
SHE HAS A MESSAGE,
AND SHE HAS TO CARRY IT.

33:25.525 --> 33:26.830
IT'S WHAT SHE DOES.

33:26.874 --> 33:27.962
THAT'S MY MESSAGE.

33:29.616 --> 33:31.487
ELSA?

33:31.531 --> 33:33.620
I'M ELSITA.
JACKSON?

33:33.663 --> 33:35.796
I'M LEM.

33:35.839 --> 33:37.319
ELSA WAS MY MAMA.

33:37.363 --> 33:39.626
JACKSON WAS
MY PRISON BUNKMATE.

33:39.669 --> 33:41.584
IS "BUNKMATE"
A EUPHEMISM FOR --

33:41.628 --> 33:43.804
NOT IN THIS CASE, MA'AM.[ THUNDER CRASHING ]

33:43.847 --> 33:45.675
Narrator: THERE WAS
A BITTER CHILL IN THE AIR

33:45.719 --> 33:49.331
THE NIGHT JACKSON LUCAS FOUND
REFUGE IN THE VonRoenn WINDMILL.

33:49.375 --> 33:51.290
ALREADY FIVE DAYS ON THE LAM,

33:51.333 --> 33:53.857
HE KNEW THE POLICE
WERE CLOSING IN.

33:53.901 --> 33:55.250
TO PRESERVE HIS DREAMS

33:55.294 --> 33:58.036
OF ONE DAY OWNING
AN ART GALLERY IN MEXICO,

33:58.079 --> 34:00.777
JACKSON DECIDED TO BURY
HIS STOLEN TREASURE

34:00.821 --> 34:03.911
IN THE STAIRCASE OF THE
SEEMINGLY ABANDONED PROPERTY.

34:03.954 --> 34:05.130
[ FLOORBOARD CREAKS ]

34:05.173 --> 34:08.046
HIS HEART STOPPED, HOWEVER,

34:08.089 --> 34:11.353
WHEN HE SAW AN ANGELIC CREATURE
DESCENDING THE STAIRS.

34:11.397 --> 34:15.357
HER NAME WAS ELSA,
AND THIS WAS HER WINDMILL.

34:15.401 --> 34:16.793
MY NAME IS ELSA.

34:16.837 --> 34:19.796
THIS IS MY WINDMILL.

34:19.840 --> 34:21.537
Narrator:
IT WAS LOVE AT FIRST SIGHT.

34:21.581 --> 34:25.150
KNOWING HE HAD VERY LITTLE TIME
LEFT, HE KISSED HER.

34:25.193 --> 34:27.848
IT WAS A PERFECT MOMENT.

34:29.197 --> 34:31.678
THE NEXT MOMENT WAS NOT.

34:35.856 --> 34:38.076
I'LL WRITE YOU!

34:38.119 --> 34:39.947
Narrator:
ELSA KEPT TRUE TO HER WORD.

34:39.990 --> 34:41.818
FOR THE NEXT 20 YEARS,

34:41.862 --> 34:45.735
SHE AND JACKSON CONTINUED THEIR
LOVE AFFAIR BY CORRESPONDENCE,

34:45.779 --> 34:47.520
LETTERS SENT TO AND FRO

34:47.563 --> 34:51.654
WITH THE HELP OF HER VIRTUALLY
UNTRACEABLE CARRIER PIGEON,

34:51.698 --> 34:55.528
UNTIL THE DAY JACKSON KNEW
HE WOULD NO LONGER BE ABLE

34:55.571 --> 34:57.878
TO KEEP HIS PROMISE.

34:57.921 --> 35:02.230
SOMEONE ELSE WOULD HAVE
TO DO IT FOR HIM.

35:02.274 --> 35:05.581
AFTER JACKSON DIED,
I STARTED TO PLAN MY ESCAPE.

35:05.625 --> 35:08.106
IT TOOK ME TWO YEARS.

35:08.149 --> 35:10.586
AND ALL THAT TIME,
I KEPT WRITING TO ELSA.

35:10.630 --> 35:13.111
FIRST, I WAS WRITING
OUT OF LOYALTY TO THE MAN

35:13.154 --> 35:14.938
WHO TAUGHT ME THE ROPES
IN PRISON,

35:14.982 --> 35:19.334
BUT AFTER A WHILE,
I STARTED TO DEVELOP...

35:19.378 --> 35:20.857
A CONDITION?

35:20.901 --> 35:24.252
FOR ELSA -- AT LEAST,
I THOUGHT IT WAS ELSA.

35:24.296 --> 35:26.080
AND MAMA MADE ME SWEAR
ON HER DEATHBED

35:26.124 --> 35:28.169
THAT I'D NEVER STOP WRITING
TO JACKSON,

35:28.213 --> 35:30.780
SAID IT WOULD BREAK HIS HEART
TO LEARN THAT SHE DIED.

35:30.824 --> 35:33.957
BUT EACH LETTER WAS MORE
BEAUTIFUL THAN THE LAST,

35:34.001 --> 35:35.611
AND I FOUND MYSELF
LOOKING FORWARD TO THEM.

35:35.655 --> 35:38.353
WELL, YOUR LETTERS
WERE BEAUTIFUL, TOO.

35:38.397 --> 35:40.399
WHAT'S THE BIG WHOOP?

35:40.442 --> 35:43.097
PIDGE BROUGHT THEM
TOGETHER.

35:43.141 --> 35:44.403
Olive:
HOW DID SHE LOSE HER WING?

35:44.446 --> 35:46.100
I TOOK HER WITH ME
ON THE PLANE

35:46.144 --> 35:47.710
WHEN I BUSTED OUT
OF PRISON.

35:47.754 --> 35:49.451
SHE FLEW OUT THE WINDOW
AFTER TAKEOFF

35:49.495 --> 35:51.149
AND WENT RIGHT
THROUGH THE PROPELLER.

35:51.192 --> 35:53.760
OH!
PIDGECRASHED THE PLANE.

35:53.803 --> 35:55.457
[ Chuckling ] OH, PIDGE.

35:55.501 --> 35:57.155
WHAT HAPPENED
TO THE DIAMONDS?

35:57.198 --> 35:58.634
Together: "DIAMONDS"?

36:02.029 --> 36:03.683
OH. OH.

36:06.599 --> 36:08.557
HOLY CRAP!

36:08.601 --> 36:09.993
HOLY CRAP!

36:10.037 --> 36:11.256
HMM.

36:12.822 --> 36:15.434
[ KNOCK ON DOOR ]

36:15.477 --> 36:16.565
[ POUNDING ON DOOR ]

36:16.609 --> 36:18.219
NOW, NOW,
LET'S NOT PANIC.

36:18.263 --> 36:19.655
I'M SURE
IT'S JUST THE MAILMAN

36:19.699 --> 36:22.571
OR A WINDMILL-TO-WINDMILL
SALESMAN.

36:22.615 --> 36:24.312
LET ME HANDLE IT.

36:30.492 --> 36:32.320
Narrator: AS OLIVE PEEPED
THROUGH THE PEEPHOLE,

36:32.364 --> 36:33.974
IT OCCURRED TO HER THAT,

36:34.017 --> 36:37.020
WHILE THE CARRIER PIGEON
WAS SAFE INSIDE THE WINDMILL,

36:37.064 --> 36:40.459
THE SAME COULD NOT BE SAID
FOR THE SITTING DUCK

36:40.502 --> 36:42.461
CURRENTLY WAITING
ON THE DOORSTEP.

36:55.648 --> 36:58.172
Narrator:
THIS WAS THE MOMENT OLIVE SNOOK
HAD BEEN WAITING FOR.

36:58.216 --> 36:59.869
SHE NEED ONLY OPEN THE DOOR

36:59.913 --> 37:02.089
TO EXPOSE CHUCK'S DECEIT
TO THE AUNTS,

37:02.132 --> 37:04.352
AND THE PIE MAKER COULD BE HERS.

37:04.396 --> 37:08.704
IT WAS EVERYTHING OLIVE WANTED,
AND YET...

37:10.140 --> 37:13.274
SHE KNEW THAT THE AUNTS
WOULD BE TRAUMATIZED

37:13.318 --> 37:15.755
BY THE DISCOVERY THAT
THE LATE CHARLOTTE CHARLES

37:15.798 --> 37:17.670
WAS LATE NO MORE.

37:17.713 --> 37:19.019
IN THAT MOMENT,

37:19.062 --> 37:21.761
OLIVE FELT THE ANGRY FIRE
IN HER HEART

37:21.804 --> 37:24.503
EXTINGUISHED BY A LIGHT BREEZE.

37:24.546 --> 37:27.723
SHE HAD GROWN FOND
OF LILY AND VIVIAN

37:27.767 --> 37:30.552
AND COULD NOT BRING HERSELF
TO HURT THEM.

37:38.343 --> 37:39.735
AFTERNOON, GANG!

37:39.779 --> 37:40.954
OLIVE?

37:40.997 --> 37:42.303
WHAT THE HELL
ARE YOU DOING HERE?

37:42.347 --> 37:44.087
PIE DELIVERY.
TART APPLE, I BELIEVE.

37:44.131 --> 37:48.353
Narrator: WITH THOSE TWO WORDS,
CHUCK KNEW.

37:49.832 --> 37:51.443
HER AUNTS WERE INSIDE.

37:51.486 --> 37:53.749
OLIVE...

37:53.793 --> 37:55.795
IF YOU KNOW WHAT'S GOOD FOR YOU,
AND I THINK YOU DO,

37:55.838 --> 37:57.100
YOU'LL GIVE ME
TWO MINUTES.

37:57.144 --> 37:58.754
WHY?
WHAT FOR?
OKAY.

37:58.798 --> 37:59.886
GOODY, THEN.

38:02.192 --> 38:04.543
[ DOOR CLOSES ]

38:04.586 --> 38:05.544
WHO WAS IT?

38:05.587 --> 38:06.893
WRONG MILL.

38:06.936 --> 38:08.721
MUST HAPPEN A LOT
AROUND HERE, HUH?

38:08.764 --> 38:10.157
ANYWAY, I FEEL JUST AWFUL

38:10.200 --> 38:12.377
THAT WE'VE TAKEN UP SO MUCH
OF YOUR DAY.

38:12.420 --> 38:13.813
WE SHOULD REALLY BE GOING.

38:13.856 --> 38:15.902
UH, DO YOU MIND IF WE USE
THE BACK DOOR?

38:15.945 --> 38:18.818
I JUST WANTED TO TAKE A PEEK
AT YOUR GARDEN ON THE WAY OUT.

38:18.861 --> 38:20.689
THANKS! BYE!

38:24.171 --> 38:25.346
NED.
HMM?

38:25.390 --> 38:27.000
DO YOU REMEMBER BEFORE,

38:27.043 --> 38:28.567
WHEN I TOLD YOU ALL THE THINGS
I'D LEARNED ABOUT YOU?

38:28.610 --> 38:30.177
JEALOUS, ROMANTIC,
JEALOUS.

38:30.220 --> 38:31.570
I FELT I HAD
TO SAY IT TWICE.

38:31.613 --> 38:33.223
RIGHT. WELL, NOW MIGHT BE
A REALLY GOOD TIME

38:33.267 --> 38:34.660
FOR YOU TO WRITE DOWN ALL
THE THINGS YOU LEARNED ABOUT ME.

38:34.703 --> 38:36.357
WHY?

38:36.401 --> 38:38.446
WELL, THAT WAY,
IF STUFF HAPPENS...

38:38.490 --> 38:40.013
JUST REMEMBER THE LIST.

38:40.056 --> 38:42.276
Emerson: TIME'S UP.

38:42.320 --> 38:45.323
WELL, NOW,
WASN'T THAT A NICE OUTING?

38:45.366 --> 38:46.889
I COULD USE A DRINK.

38:46.933 --> 38:50.502
YOUNG PEOPLE DEPRESS LILY
BECAUSE SHE'S AFRAID OF DYING.

38:50.545 --> 38:53.548
Narrator: AS LILY WONDERED
WHETHER SHE WAS AFRAID OF DYING

38:53.592 --> 38:55.898
OR SIMPLY MISSED FEELING ALIVE,

38:55.942 --> 38:59.728
SHE ALLOWED HERSELF ONE DEEP
BREATH OF FRESH COUNTRY AIR.

38:59.772 --> 39:01.208
[ INHALES,
EXHALES DEEPLY ]

39:01.251 --> 39:05.081
I DON'T THINK WE'VE BEEN
OUT SINCE -- CHARLOTTE?!

39:07.736 --> 39:09.390
NO NEED TO YELL HER NAME.

39:09.434 --> 39:12.262
I THINK HEAVEN'S CLOSER
THAN WE THINK.

39:12.306 --> 39:13.742
I AGREE.

39:15.440 --> 39:16.702
HMM!

39:16.745 --> 39:17.616
HANDUP!

39:22.272 --> 39:23.622
[ CLICKING ]

39:30.368 --> 39:33.022
[ CHUCKLES ]

39:33.066 --> 39:35.242
LEMUEL, I'LL WRITE YOU!

39:38.201 --> 39:41.335
Narrator: THE PIE MAKER
AND THE GIRL HE CALLED "CHUCK"

39:41.379 --> 39:45.034
MARVELED AT LOVE'S POWER
TO CONQUER ALL OBSTACLES --

39:45.078 --> 39:47.341
DISTANCE AND TIME...

39:47.385 --> 39:50.344
HARDSHIP AND PAIN...

39:52.955 --> 39:57.438
A LACK OF RECIPROCATION...

39:57.482 --> 39:59.788
EVEN DEATH.

39:59.832 --> 40:01.660
YOUR HUSBAND
WAS A GREAT PILOT.

40:01.703 --> 40:04.750
HE DIDN'T KILL HIMSELF.
A PIGEON DID, BY ACCIDENT.

40:06.491 --> 40:07.492
[ COOING ]

40:07.535 --> 40:09.145
Narrator:
WITH PIDGE'S HELP,

40:09.189 --> 40:11.452
THE LONG-DISTANCE LOVE AFFAIR
OF LEFTY AND ELSITA

40:11.496 --> 40:13.759
CONTINUED TO SOAR.

40:13.802 --> 40:16.326
AND THE PIE MAKER REALIZED THAT,

40:16.370 --> 40:19.982
WHILE SOME OBSTACLES
MAY NEVER DISAPPEAR...

40:21.810 --> 40:23.682
CARE TO DANCE?

40:23.725 --> 40:26.511
HMM. YES, PLEASE.

40:29.514 --> 40:31.516
[ CLASSICAL MUSIC PLAYS ]

40:31.559 --> 40:35.911
Narrator: ...YOU CAN ALWAYS FIND
A WAY TO WORK AROUND THEM.

40:46.400 --> 40:48.794
[ CHUCK GIGGLES ]

40:48.837 --> 40:51.405
DIP?

40:51.449 --> 40:52.798
[ GASPS ]

40:52.841 --> 40:54.364
YOU CAUGHT ME.

41:07.769 --> 41:10.076
[ BOTH LAUGH ]
